  - message: "Newton\u2019s First Law, the Law of Inertia, states that an object
      will remain in its current state unless there is a change in its equilibrium
      caused by an unbalanced, outside force."
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 0
    endTime: 1
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Like my hovercraft coasting straight unless wind or brakes interfere.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 1
    endTime: 2
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "Yes. That\u2019s equilibrium it occurs when opposing influences or
      forces are balanced, resulting in a stable situation where no change is occurring."
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 3
    endTime: 4
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Balanced forces keep me steady, unbalanced ones shove me into new motion.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 4
    endTime: 5
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "Exactly. That leads to Newton\u2019s Second Law\u2014Law of Acceleration.
      An object is said to be accelerating if an unbalanced net force is applied
      to it."
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 6
    endTime: 7
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "That\u2019s F = ma, right?"
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 7
    endTime: 8
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Yes. Force equals mass times acceleration. Heavier hovercraft needs
      more thrust to match acceleration of a lighter one.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 0
    startTime: 0
    endTime: 0
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Like pushing a boulder versus a soccer ball.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 0
    startTime: 0
    endTime: 0
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Force is defined as an influence that tends to change an object's state
      of motion when left unopposed. It also means strength or energy result of physical
      action.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 9
    endTime: 10
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: So every push in racing is a Newton battle.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 10
    endTime: 11
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Now, types of forces. Contact forces first. Contact Force are forces
      that two object exert whenever they are in a perceived physical contact.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 12
    endTime: 13
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "Contact\u2014like bumping rivals?"
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 13
    endTime: 14
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Exactly. Applied force is your thrust or collision.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 0
    startTime: 0
    endTime: 0
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: And tension force?
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 0
    startTime: 0
    endTime: 0
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Think of a tow cable pulling your hover back to the pits. Tension force
      is the pulling force exerted by a rope, string, or cable when pulled right.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 15
    endTime: 16
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Normal force must be the track pushing up against my weight.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 16
    endTime: 17
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Right. Friction? It is the resistance of a surface or an object acting
      upon another object in contact with in.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 18
    endTime: 19
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: And noncontact forces?
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 19
    endTime: 20
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: 'Noncontact Forces, on the other hand, are forces that two objects exert
      at a distance. '
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 21
    endTime: 22
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: So forces act whether I see them or not.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 22
    endTime: 23
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "Newton\u2019s Third Law. The premise of this Law is simple there is
      always an equal reaction and opposing amount of forc counteracting against
      another force. "
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 24
    endTime: 25
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "Like slamming rivals\u2014they bounce me back just as hard."
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 25
    endTime: 26
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Yes! The two force, when paired together are called interaction force-paires.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 27
    endTime: 28
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "It\u2019s like the track and my craft are always negotiating."
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 28
    endTime: 29
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Exactly, {player}. Physics is constant negotiation.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 0
    startTime: 0
    endTime: 0
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
